<p><b>Robert Wright</b> (born 1957 in <a href="/wiki/Lawton,_Oklahoma" title="Lawton, Oklahoma">Lawton, Oklahoma</a>) is an <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">American</a> journalist, scholar, and <a href="/wiki/Robert_Wright_(journalist)#Awards" title="Robert Wright (journalist)">prize-winning</a> author of best-selling books about science, <a href="/wiki/Evolutionary_psychology" title="Evolutionary psychology">evolutionary psychology</a>, history, religion, and <a href="/wiki/Game_theory" title="Game theory">game theory</a>, including <i><a href="/wiki/Nonzero:_The_Logic_of_Human_Destiny" title="Nonzero: The Logic of Human Destiny">Nonzero: The Logic of Human Destiny</a></i>, <i><a href="/wiki/The_Moral_Animal" title="The Moral Animal">The Moral Animal</a></i>, and <i>Three Scientists and Their Gods: Looking for Meaning in an Age of Information</i>. He is a visiting scholar at <a href="/wiki/University_of_Pennsylvania" title="University of Pennsylvania">The University of Pennsylvania</a> and Schwartz Senior Fellow at the <a href="/wiki/New_America_Foundation" title="New America Foundation">New America Foundation</a>.</p>
